    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1807_01_25_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthstown</placeName> <note>7</note>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
                        <date when="1807-01-25">25 Jan<hi rend="superscript">y </hi> 7. </date></dateline> 
                    
                        D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> . <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir</persName></opener>
                        <p> 
                    
                        I take the liberty of introducing to<lb/>
                        you my son <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">C. Sneyd Edgeworth</persName>: He intends to<lb/>
                        go to the Bar; and during the time that he is<lb/>
                        eating his way to the Courts I cannot procure for<lb/>
                        him any advantage so great, as the conversation of<lb/>
                        such men as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Monsieur Dumont.</persName><lb/></p>
                        <p>
                        Were he entirely ignorant of preliminary<lb/>
                        studies even your conversation could not serve<lb/>
                        him; but, if the partiality of a father has not<lb/>
                        blinded me, I think you will find him to be<lb/>
                        a young man of uncorrupted morals, good<lb/>
                        manners, and free from that presumption<lb/>
                        which frequently accompanies early talents.<lb/></p>
                        <p>
                        I hope that he has sufficient prudence to<lb/>
                        restrain him from intruding too often, or<lb/>
                        too long, upon your time: If from your<lb/>
                        politeness or his indiscretion the contrary<lb/>
                        should happen, I shall heartily regret having<lb/>
                        written this letter.<lb/></p>
                        <closer>
                        I have the honour to be<lb/>
                        my D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sir<lb/>
                        Your obedient &amp; humble<lb/>
                        Servant<lb/>
                        Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> Lovell Edgeworth<lb/></closer>
                        
                   
                    
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
